# TypeScript Coding Standards â€” CursorBlame

## Strict mode

The project uses `"strict": true` in [tsconfig.json](mdc:tsconfig.json). All code MUST compile cleanly under strict mode:
- No implicit `any`.
- Strict null checks (`null` and `undefined` must be handled explicitly).
- No unused locals or parameters (suppress intentional ones with `void varName`).

Always run `npm run typecheck` (`tsc --noEmit`) before considering a change complete.

## Type-first design

- Export **interfaces and types** from [types.ts](mdc:src/types.ts). Keep that file as the single source of truth for shared data structures.
- Prefer `type` imports (`import type { ... }`) when importing only types â€” this produces zero runtime code.
- Avoid `any`. Use `unknown` with type guards when the type is genuinely not known.
- Function return types SHOULD be annotated explicitly for all exported functions.

## VS Code Extension API conventions

- The extension entry point is [extension.ts](mdc:src/extension.ts) which exports `activate()` and `deactivate()`.
- All event listeners, watchers, and commands MUST be pushed to `context.subscriptions` so they are auto-disposed.
- Use `vscode.TextEditorDecorationType` for visual overlays â€” never manipulate document text to show annotations.
- Debounce high-frequency events (selection change) to avoid performance degradation.
- Respect `vscode.workspace.isTrusted` â€” never run git commands in untrusted workspaces.

## Module boundaries

Each source file has a single clear responsibility:

| File | Responsibility | May import from |
|------|---------------|-----------------|
| `types.ts` | Shared interfaces/types | (none) |
| `gitBlame.ts` | Execute git, parse porcelain | `types` |
| `blameCache.ts` | LRU cache for blame data | `types` |
| `remoteUrl.ts` | Remote detection, URL building | `types`, `gitBlame` (isValidSha) |
| `decoration.ts` | Decoration rendering | `types`, `remoteUrl` (commitUrl) |
| `extension.ts` | Lifecycle, events, commands | all modules |

- Do NOT introduce circular dependencies.
- Do NOT import `vscode` in `types.ts`, `gitBlame.ts`, or `blameCache.ts` â€” they must remain VS Code-agnostic for testability.
- Only `extension.ts` and `decoration.ts` may import `vscode`.

## Error handling

- Git operations may fail (untracked files, detached HEAD, no repo). Always handle errors gracefully â€” return `null` and clear the decoration.
- NEVER show error dialogs for expected failures (e.g. file not in git). Use `console.warn` or silent suppression.
- Only use `vscode.window.showWarningMessage` for user-initiated actions that fail (e.g. "Open commit on remote" with no remote).

## Async patterns

- Use `async/await` over raw Promises for readability.
- Wrap `execFile` callbacks in Promises (see `runGit()` in [gitBlame.ts](mdc:src/gitBlame.ts)).
- Catch and suppress errors in fire-and-forget calls: `.catch(() => {})`.

## Style

- Use `const` by default; `let` only when reassignment is necessary. Never use `var`.
- Prefer `===` over `==`.
- Use template literals for string interpolation, but NEVER for constructing shell commands (see security rules).
- Named exports only (no default exports).
- Keep functions small and focused â€” extract helpers with descriptive names.
- JSDoc every exported function. Internal helpers should have at least a one-liner comment.
- Use `readonly` for class properties that should not be reassigned after construction.

## Build

- The build uses esbuild ([esbuild.js](mdc:esbuild.js)) to bundle all TypeScript into a single `dist/extension.js`.
- `vscode` is declared as an external â€” it is provided by the host editor at runtime.
- Target: Node 16 / CJS.
- NEVER edit files in `dist/` directly â€” they are generated artifacts.
